Generalized Pauli constraints in small atoms

Christian Schilling Christian.Schilling@physics.ox.ac.uk Clarendon Laboratory, University of Oxford, Parks Road, Oxford OX1 3PU, United Kingdom    Murat Altunbulak Department of Mathematics, Faculty of Science, Dokuz Eylul University, 35390 Buca-Izmir, Turkey    Stefan Knecht ETH Zürich, Laboratorium für Physikalische Chemie, Vladimir-Prelog-Weg 2, 8093 Zürich, Switzerland    Alexandre Lopes Carl Zeiss SMT GmbH, Rudolf-Eber-Straße 2, 73447 Oberkochen, Germany    James D. Whitfield Department of Physics and Astronomy, Dartmouth College, 6127 Wilder Laboratory, Hanover, NH 03755, USA    Matthias Christandl QMATH, Department of Mathematical Sciences, University of Copenhagen, Universitetsparken 5, 2100 Copenhagen, Denmark    David Gross Institute for Theoretical Physics, University of Cologne, Zülpicher Straße 77, 50937 Cologne, Germany    Markus Reiher ETH Zürich, Laboratorium für Physikalische Chemie, Vladimir-Prelog-Weg 2, 8093 Zürich, Switzerland
Abstract

The natural occupation numbers of fermionic systems are subject to non-trivial constraints, which include and extend the original Pauli principle. A recent mathematical breakthrough has clarified their mathematical structure and has opened up the possibility of a systematic analysis. Early investigations have found evidence that these constraints are exactly saturated in several physically relevant systems; e.g. in a certain electronic state of the Beryllium atom. It has been suggested that in such cases, the constraints, rather than the details of the Hamiltonian, dictate the system’s qualitative behavior. Here, we revisit this question with state-of-the-art numerical methods for small atoms. We find that the constraints are, in fact, not exactly saturated, but that they lie much closer to the surface defined by the constraints than the geometry of the problem would suggest. While the results seem incompatible with the statement that the generalized Pauli constraints drive the behavior of these systems, they suggest that the qualitatively correct wave-function expansions can in some systems already be obtained on the basis of a limited number of Slater determinants, which is in line with numerical evidence from quantum chemistry.

I Introduction

Pauli’s exclusion principle Pauli (1925) is a well-known physical principle. Its relevance concerns all length scales, from the subatomic (structure of nuclei) up to the astronomic scale (stability of neutron stars). The most prominent example for its relevance, however, is the Aufbau principle underlying the periodic table and explaining the structure of atoms. In the 1970s, it was found that the fermionic exchange symmetry implies further constraints on natural occupation numbers Borland and Dennis (1972); Ruskai (2007). Remarkably, it took several decades before their mathematical structure was finally understood and a complete classification could be derived Klyachko (2006); Altunbulak and Klyachko (2008); Altunbulak (2008). To be more specific, these so-called generalized Pauli constraints (GPCs) take the form of linear conditions,

In Eq. (1), the κj(k)superscriptsubscript𝜅𝑗𝑘\kappa_{j}^{(k)} are the coefficients specifying the j𝑗jth linear inequality with the N𝑁N-fermion quantum state |ΨN⟩∈∧N[ℋ1(d)]ketsubscriptΨ𝑁superscript𝑁delimited-[]superscriptsubscriptℋ1𝑑\mbox{$|\Psi_{N}\rangle$}\in\wedge^{N}[\mathcal{H}_{1}^{(d)}], where the one-particle Hilbert space ℋ1(d)superscriptsubscriptℋ1𝑑\mathcal{H}_{1}^{(d)} has dimension d𝑑d. For each setting (N,d)𝑁𝑑(N,d), there are finitely many GPCs, which define a convex polytope 𝒫⊂ℝd𝒫superscriptℝ𝑑\mathcal{P}\subset{\mathbb{R}}^{d}. It is a subset of the Pauli simplex ΔΔ\Delta defined by the original Pauli constraints 1≥λ1≥…≥λd≥01subscript𝜆1…subscript𝜆𝑑01\geq\lambda_{1}\geq\ldots\geq\lambda_{d}\geq 0.

In an ongoing debate, the physical relevance of the GPCs has been explored and discussed Klyachko (2009); Schilling et al. (2013); Benavides-Riveros et al. (2013); Klyachko (2013); Chakraborty and Mazziotti (2014); Schilling (2014); Chakraborty and Mazziotti (2015a); Schilling (2015a); Benavides-Riveros and Springborg (2015); Theophilou et al. (2015); Chakraborty and Mazziotti (2015b); Lopes (2015); Schilling (2015b); Wang and Knowles (2015); Benavides-Riveros (2015); Tennie et al. (2016a); Chakraborty and Mazziotti (2016); Tennie et al. (2016b); Mazziotti (2016); Benavides-Riveros et al. (2017); Chakraborty and Mazziotti (2017); Tennie (2017); Walter et al. (2013); Sawicki et al. (2012); Maciażek and Tsanov (2017); Legeza and Schilling (2018); Benavides-Riveros (2018). An early numerical result suggested that a specific state of the Be atom (see below) would saturate some of the GPCs Klyachko (2009). Based on this observation, the pinning phenomenon has been conjectured: The variational minimization of the energy functional, from the point of view of the one-particle picture, may settle on the polytope boundary ∂𝒫𝒫\partial\mathcal{P}. In analogy to the way the string of a pendulum restricts the movement of the attached mass, the GPCs would then constrain the kinematics of the system to a lower-dimensional space, which would shape the qualitative behavior of the system—e.g. its response to external perturbations Klyachko (2009, 2013); Schilling (2015b); Maciażek et al. (2017).

Due to its striking consequences, a central question is whether exact pinning actually occurs in realistic fermionic quantum systems. While analytic results for a harmonic model system suggest a negative answer Schilling et al. (2013); Tennie et al. (2016a, b), various studies of small atoms and molecules Klyachko (2009); Chakraborty and Mazziotti (2014); Theophilou et al. (2015); Chakraborty and Mazziotti (2015b); Schilling (2015b); Chakraborty and Mazziotti (2016) seem to confirm the occurrence of pinning in ground states, and hence emphasize the relevance of the GPCs in quantum chemistry. However, these numerical studies may be inconclusive for two reasons: First, they are based on very small active spaces of only 6 to 10 spin-orbitals and might therefore fail to accurately capture the true physical situation. Second, it has only been recently realized that exact or approximate pinning (quasipinning) is in some cases implied merely by the geometry of the polytope 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P} and the saturation of some of the original Pauli constraints Tennie et al. (2017).

In the present work, we revisit the problem and address the above concerns. In particular: (i) We use state-of-the-art numerical methods (involving up to 1000 spin-orbitals) to reproduce the atomic natural occupation numbers to high precision. (ii) We perform a careful analysis of truncation errors. (iii) We employ a precise quantitative measure to distinguish geometrically trivial from non-trivial pinning.

We note in passing that a vast body of numerical data on atoms and molecules obtained in quantum chemistry in the past decades has led to a classification of electron correlation (and, in turn, of features of sets of natural occupation numbers) that is governed by the external potential generated by the atomic nuclei in the system. In this context, we recall that the GPCs follow, however, solely from the fermionic exchange symmetry. Just like Pauli’s exclusion principle, they are therefore valid for all fermionic quantum systems, independent of the concrete physics involved (Hamiltonian).

In order to elucidate in a quantitative fashion the saturation of the GPCs for an electronic structure of the system under investigation, we restrict ourselves in this work to a study of simple atomic systems such as Li and Be, for which we can provide sufficiently accurate numerical quantum chemical data obtained from full-configuration-interaction (FCI) calculations close to the basis-set limit.

The main result of our analysis is that the states originally investigated in the literature are not exactly pinned. At the same time, the natural occupation numbers lie much closer to the facets of the polytope 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P} than its geometry would imply (a phenomenon we referred to as non-trivial quasipinning Tennie et al. (2017)). This is an important distinction: Both the original physical interpretation (that the response of pinned systems to perturbations is restricted by the saturated constraints), as well as the most plausible physical mechanism giving rise to pinning in ground states (that the GPCs prevents a further reduction of the ground state energy) require exact pinning. At the same time, recent results Schilling (2015a); Schilling et al. (2017) show that wave functions whose natural occupation numbers lie close to the boundary can be well-approximated by a superposition of a small number of very specific Slater determinants. This so-called super-selection rule for Slater determinants Klyachko (2009) reflects and expands the vast numerical knowledge obtained in the quantum-chemistry community concerning the structure of atomic ground states. In this sense, generalized Pauli constraints do have physical implications for small atoms, which might, however, be different from the ones originally anticipated.

II Methods

In order to achieve the results outlined above, we had to meet three technical challenges:

First, in order to obtain sufficiently accurate approximations to the natural occupation numbers, we had to find the variational ground states in Hilbert spaces spanned by up to 1000 spin-orbitals (rather than just 6 to 10 as in previous works Klyachko (2009); Chakraborty and Mazziotti (2014); Theophilou et al. (2015); Chakraborty and Mazziotti (2015b); Schilling (2015b); Chakraborty and Mazziotti (2016)). Our numerical optimizations are accurate enough to recover more than 99% of the correlation energy (As measured for example by a comparison of our best variational energy of -14.6667932644 hartree with the up-to-date best variational energy of -14.667356498 hartree for the S1superscript𝑆1{}^{1}S spin sector of the Be atom Puchalski et al. (2013)). This consistency check gives us great confidence that, at the very least, the qualitative results derived from the numerical data (absence of pinning and presence of non-trivial quasipinning) will hold for the exact ground states of the respective atoms as well.

Second, we had to cope with the problem that the numerics returns up to 1000 occupation numbers (corresponding to the number of spin-orbitals), whereas the GPCs were explicitly known only for settings up to dimension d=10𝑑10d=10. While systematic algorithms for determining all GPCs exist, the required computational effort increases dramatically with increasing d𝑑d Altunbulak (2008); Vergne and Walter (2014); Bürgisser et al. (2017). Fortunately, most of the 1000 numerically obtained occupation numbers λ→→𝜆\vec{\lambda} are either very close to 111 or to 00. It therefore appears plausible that one can carry out a pinning analysis in terms of a truncated version λ→′superscript→𝜆′\vec{\lambda}^{\prime} of λ→→𝜆\vec{\lambda}, obtained by ignoring these extreme eigenvalues. Indeed, a method to obtain quantitative estimates of errors introduced through truncation have recently been developed Schilling (2014); Tennie et al. (2016a). To be more precise, we quantify quasipinning by the minimal l1subscript𝑙1l_{1}-distance Dm​i​n≡dist1​(λ→,∂𝒫)subscript𝐷𝑚𝑖𝑛subscriptdist1→𝜆𝒫D_{min}\equiv\mbox{dist}_{1}\big{(}\vec{\lambda},\partial\mathcal{P}\big{)} of λ→→𝜆\vec{\lambda} to the polytope boundary. We reduce N𝑁N to N′superscript𝑁′N^{\prime} by ignoring eigenvalues close to 111, and d𝑑d to d′superscript𝑑′d^{\prime} by also ignoring those close to 00. We denote the minimal distance found in the analysis in the truncated setting (N′,d′)superscript𝑁′superscript𝑑′(N^{\prime},d^{\prime}) with polytope 𝒫′superscript𝒫′\mathcal{P}^{\prime} by Dm​i​n′≡dist1​(λ→′,∂𝒫′)subscriptsuperscript𝐷′𝑚𝑖𝑛subscriptdist1superscript→𝜆′superscript𝒫′D^{\prime}_{min}\equiv\mbox{dist}_{1}\big{(}\vec{\lambda}^{\prime},\partial\mathcal{P}^{\prime}\big{)}. Under reasonable technical assumptions on the asymptotic behavior of GPCs, one can relate Dm​i​n′subscriptsuperscript𝐷′𝑚𝑖𝑛D^{\prime}_{min} to Dm​i​nsubscript𝐷𝑚𝑖𝑛D_{min} in the full setting by virtue of the truncation error ε′superscript𝜀′\varepsilon^{\prime} (see also Appendix A):

|Dm​i​n−Dm​i​n′|≤ε′≡∑j=1N−N′(1−λj)+∑k=0d−d′−N′+N−1λd−k.subscript𝐷𝑚𝑖𝑛subscriptsuperscript𝐷′𝑚𝑖𝑛superscript𝜀′superscriptsubscript𝑗1𝑁superscript𝑁′1subscript𝜆𝑗superscriptsubscript𝑘0𝑑superscript𝑑′superscript𝑁′𝑁1subscript𝜆𝑑𝑘\big{|}D_{min}-D^{\prime}_{min}\big{|}\leq\varepsilon^{\prime}\equiv\sum_{j=1}^{N-N^{\prime}}(1-\lambda_{j})+\!\!\sum_{k=0}^{d-d^{\prime}-N^{\prime}+N-1}\!\!\lambda_{d-k}\,. (2)

Since the minimally required reduced dimension d′superscript𝑑′d^{\prime} allowing for a conclusive pinning analysis turns out to be larger than the maximal d′superscript𝑑′d^{\prime} for which the GPCs were known so far, we have performed extensive calculations to determine the GPCs also for the settings (N′,d′)=(3,11),(3,12)superscript𝑁′superscript𝑑′311312(N^{\prime},d^{\prime})=(3,11),(3,12) (see Appendix C).

Third, quasipinning by the generalized Pauli constraints can in some cases arise as a mere consequence of quasipinning by the original ones. Indeed, any given set of eigenvalues λ→→𝜆\vec{\lambda} is at least as close to ∂𝒫𝒫\partial\mathcal{P} as it is to ∂ΔΔ\partial\Delta (this holds because all physically attainable boundary points of the Pauli simplex ΔΔ\Delta are also boundary points of 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P}). It can therefore be argued that pinning to the GPC should only be considered as non-trivial, if the distance of λ→→𝜆\vec{\lambda} to ∂P𝑃\partial P is much smaller than the distance of λ→→𝜆\vec{\lambda} to ∂ΔΔ\partial\Delta. To assess the “degree of non-triviality” quantitatively, we will employ the so-called Q𝑄Q-parameter constructed in Ref. 35.

There are two conclusions to be drawn: On the one hand, the more precise analysis shows that the seemingly exactly pinned vector λ→→𝜆\vec{\lambda} does not lie on the boundary of the eigenvalue polytope after all. On the other hand, it is true that the distance from the boundary is surprisingly small. Before turning to further examples, we briefly discuss the deviation in Eq. (4) from exact pinning quantitatively. For a rough sense of scale, one can compare Eq. (4) to the polytope diameter which is on the order of 111. However, as explained in the Introduction, we also need to ensure that this degree of quasipinning is non-trivial in the sense of not being implied by the near-saturation of the original Pauli constraints. For example, according to Table 1, the first four eigenvalues differ from their allowed maximum by no more than 10−3superscript10310^{-3}, which already implies that quasipinning of at least this strength has to be present. A complete analysis in terms of the Q𝑄Q-parameter Tennie et al. (2017) confirms that the GPCs are, in fact, physically relevant for the electronic state of the Be atom at hand: The deviation from exact pinning is smaller by a factor of about 245245245 from what the value implied merely by the saturation of the Pauli constraints (see Appendix B).

The previous result pertained to a variational calculation within a subspace spanned by very few orbitals. To obtain a more physically accurate description of the Be atom in the triplet state under consideration, one would need to include orbitals with non-zero angular momentum. However, we first pursue a different route by extending only the number of s𝑠s-orbitals with the aim to determine to high precision the variational ground state within this (artificial) Hilbert space. The motivation is as follows: Such freezing of degenerate angular degrees of freedom increases the conflict between energy minimization and fermionic exchange symmetry, which has been argued to increase the strength of quasipinning Tennie et al. (2016a, b). In contrast to the previous analysis of the state involving only five s𝑠s-orbitals the following analyses will require us to truncate the numerically obtained eigenvalues: It will not be possible anymore to explore (quasi)pinning in the full settings since the GPCs for four electrons are known only for active spaces spanned by up to five spatial orbitals.

Convergence on the significant digits has been achieved not only for the energy but also for the occupation numbers (see Appendix E). The analysis of the non-triviality of these findings shows that the GPCs have a physical relevance since their approximate saturation is stronger by a factor 37.737.737.7 than the one of the Pauli constraints.

We complete our investigation of the role of the GPCs in small atoms by returning to the Be atom. There are three spin sectors, corresponding to the total spins S=2,1,0𝑆210S=2,1,0. The case of a singlet state, S=0𝑆0S=0, does not allow for any non-trivial relevance of the GPCs. This is based on the fact that for singlet states and in general for states of evenly many fermions with doubly degenerate natural occupation numbers, the GPCs coincide with the original Pauli constraints Smith (1966). From a geometric viewpoint, the polytope 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P} and the larger Pauli simplex ΔΔ\Delta coincide after their restriction to the hyperplane described by λ1=λ2,λ3=λ4,…formulae-sequencesubscript𝜆1subscript𝜆2subscript𝜆3subscript𝜆4…\lambda_{1}=\lambda_{2},\,\lambda_{3}=\lambda_{4},\ldots. Since we already analyzed the lowest-lying S𝑆S=1 state of Be, we now consider the case of the lowest-lying quintet state (S𝑆S=2). The numerically exact natural occupation numbers for fully polarized electrons are listed in Appendix E and the results of the truncated pinning analysis are illustrated in Fig. 1. Since 1−λ1=3.34⋅10−41subscript𝜆1⋅3.34superscript1041-\lambda_{1}=3.34\cdot 10^{-4} is (much) smaller than λ11=λ12=2.14⋅10−3subscript𝜆11subscript𝜆12⋅2.14superscript103\lambda_{11}=\lambda_{12}=2.14\cdot 10^{-3} we choose as truncated settings (3,d′)3superscript𝑑′(3,d^{\prime}) with d′=6−12superscript𝑑′612d^{\prime}=6-12 rather than (4,d′)4superscript𝑑′(4,d^{\prime}) with d′≤10superscript𝑑′10d^{\prime}\leq 10. The respective truncation errors are given again by Eq. (2) but now with N−N′=1>0𝑁superscript𝑁′10N-N^{\prime}=1>0. Since for the largest truncated setting, (N′,d′)≡(3,12)superscript𝑁′superscript𝑑′312(N^{\prime},d^{\prime})\equiv(3,12), the truncation error ε′=1.74⋅10−3superscript𝜀′⋅1.74superscript103\varepsilon^{\prime}=1.74\cdot 10^{-3} is smaller than the minimal distance Dm​i​n′=4.56⋅10−3subscriptsuperscript𝐷′𝑚𝑖𝑛⋅4.56superscript103D^{\prime}_{min}=4.56\cdot 10^{-3} found in that setting, no pinning is present in the full setting (4,800)4800(4,800), i.e. Dm​i​n>0subscript𝐷𝑚𝑖𝑛0D_{min}>0. Moreover, one can show that this weaker quasipinning is completely trivial: This follows immediately from the fact that the approximate saturation of some Pauli constraints is comparable.

Appendix A Quantifying quasipinning and concept of truncation

As already explained in the main text, the GPC together with the ordering constraints λ1≥…≥λd≥0subscript𝜆1…subscript𝜆𝑑0\lambda_{1}\geq\ldots\geq\lambda_{d}\geq 0 and the normalization ∑j=1dλj=Nsuperscriptsubscript𝑗1𝑑subscript𝜆𝑗𝑁\sum_{j=1}^{d}\lambda_{j}=N give rise to a polytope 𝒫(N,d)⊂ℝdsuperscript𝒫𝑁𝑑superscriptℝ𝑑\mathcal{P}^{(N,d)}\subset{\mathbb{R}}^{d}. In principle, we may quantify the strength of quasipinning of λ→∈𝒫(N,d)→𝜆superscript𝒫𝑁𝑑\vec{\lambda}\in\mathcal{P}^{(N,d)} by the l1subscript𝑙1l_{1}-distance of λ→→𝜆\vec{\lambda} to the polytope boundary. Yet, a few comments are in order. First, by “boundary” we refer in this context only to that part of the total boundary of the polytope which corresponds to saturation of some GPC (but not to saturation of an ordering constraint λi−λi+1≥0subscript𝜆𝑖subscript𝜆𝑖10\lambda_{i}-\lambda_{i+1}\geq 0). Second, it has proven convenient to determine for each GPC D𝐷D the minimal distance not to the polytope facet FDsubscript𝐹𝐷F_{D} (corresponding to D≡0𝐷0D\equiv 0) but to the hyperplane EDsubscript𝐸𝐷E_{D} obtained by linearly extending FDsubscript𝐹𝐷F_{D} and after relaxing the normalization (allowing for a minimum which is attained outside of 𝒫(N,d)superscript𝒫𝑁𝑑\mathcal{P}^{(N,d)}). One verifies then Schilling (2015a) that the l1subscript𝑙1l_{1}-distance of λ→→𝜆\vec{\lambda} to that hyperplane EDsubscript𝐸𝐷E_{D} follows as

dist1​(λ→,ED)=D​(λ→)max1≤j≤d​(|κ(j)|).subscriptdist1→𝜆subscript𝐸𝐷𝐷→𝜆subscriptmax1𝑗𝑑superscript𝜅𝑗\mbox{dist}_{1}(\vec{\lambda},E_{D})=\frac{D(\vec{\lambda})}{\mbox{max}_{1\leq j\leq d}\left(|\kappa^{(j)}|\right)}\,. (5)

For (quasi)pinning analyses in practice one faces a major problem. On the one hand, the complete family of GPC is known so far only for the settings (N,d)𝑁𝑑(N,d) up to d=10𝑑10d=10 Altunbulak (2008) and also, as calculated for this work, for (3,11),(3,12)311312(3,11),(3,12). On the other hand, most few-fermion models are based on very large or even infinite-dimensional one-particle Hilbert space. A common (see, e.g., Refs. Klyachko (2009); Benavides-Riveros et al. (2013); Chakraborty and Mazziotti (2014); Benavides-Riveros and Springborg (2015); Theophilou et al. (2015)), but less optimal way to circumvent that problem is to truncate the one-particle Hilbert space ℋ1subscriptℋ1\mathcal{H}_{1} from the very beginning to just d≤10𝑑10d\leq 10 dimensions and restrict the Hamiltonian to the corresponding subspace ∧N[ℋ1(d)]superscript𝑁delimited-[]superscriptsubscriptℋ1𝑑\wedge^{N}[\mathcal{H}_{1}^{(d)}]. For most physical models, however, this drastic approximation does not allow one to conclusively explore the occurrence of (quasi)pinning for the exact ground state as our work has shown. Besides the objection that the system may be in general too correlated in order to justify such a truncation also an erroneous choice of ℋ1(d)superscriptsubscriptℋ1𝑑\mathcal{H}_{1}^{(d)} can lead to dubious results on (quasi)pinning.

Appendix B Analysis with the Q𝑄Q-parameter

We briefly comment on the concept of the Q𝑄Q-parameter. Since the polytope 𝒫𝒫\mathcal{P} defined by the GPC is a proper subset of the Pauli simplex ΔΔ\Delta, 𝒫⊂Δ𝒫Δ\mathcal{P}\subset\Delta, pinning and quasipinning by GPC can in some cases be a consequence of (quasi)pinning by the Pauli constraints. From a geometrical viewpoint this is obvious: Whenever λ→∈𝒫⊂Δ→𝜆𝒫Δ\vec{\lambda}\in\mathcal{P}\subset\Delta is close to ∂ΔΔ\partial\Delta it is at least as close to the boundary ∂𝒫𝒫\partial\mathcal{P}. Hence, the important question is whether (quasi)pinning by GPC is stronger than possible (quasi)pinning by the Pauli constraints, i.e. whether the distance of λ→→𝜆\vec{\lambda} to the polytope boundary is much smaller than its distance to the boundary of the surrounding Pauli simplex ΔΔ\Delta. Actually, this is even more subtle: In some cases, the strongest (quasi)pinning, let’s say to the facet FDsubscript𝐹𝐷F_{D} corresponding to saturation of the GPC D𝐷D, might be trivial, yet weaker quasipinning to another polytope facet FD′subscript𝐹superscript𝐷′F_{D^{\prime}} might be non-trivial. In that case the relevance of the family of GPC would be based on GPC D′superscript𝐷′D^{\prime}. Hence, the non-triviality of pinning and quasipinning by GPC needs to be addressed for every GPC D𝐷D, i.e. for every facet FDsubscript𝐹𝐷F_{D}, separately. This leads to a highly involved geometrical problem which has been solved in Ref. Tennie et al. (2017). In particular, for every GPC D𝐷D it has been determine how many occupation numbers need to be pinned by the Pauli constraints to the values 0 and 1 to enforce saturation of D𝐷D. Then, by denoting the minimally required number of occupation numbers equal to 0 and 1 by r𝑟r and s𝑠s, respectively, the flat geometry of the polytope implies relations of the form

D​(λ→)≤c​Sr,s​(λ→).𝐷→𝜆𝑐subscript𝑆𝑟𝑠→𝜆D(\vec{\lambda})\leq cS_{r,s}(\vec{\lambda})\,. (16)

Here, Sr,ssubscript𝑆𝑟𝑠S_{r,s} denotes the collective Pauli exclusion principle constraint corresponding to the pair (r,s)𝑟𝑠(r,s), i.e.

Sr,s​(λ→)≡∑i=1r(1−λi)+∑j=d−s+1dλj≥0subscript𝑆𝑟𝑠→𝜆superscriptsubscript𝑖1𝑟1subscript𝜆𝑖superscriptsubscript𝑗𝑑𝑠1𝑑subscript𝜆𝑗0S_{r,s}(\vec{\lambda})\equiv\sum_{i=1}^{r}(1-\lambda_{i})+\sum_{j=d-s+1}^{d}\lambda_{j}\geq 0 (17)

and c𝑐c is a geometric prefactor. The ratio of both sides in Eq. (16) then describes the non-triviality of possible quasipinning by the GPC D𝐷D. We will resort in our work to a corresponding non-triviality measure based on such ratios, the so-called Q𝑄Q-parameter Tennie et al. (2017).

For instance, the analysis in the setting (4,10)410(4,10) has shown that (quasi)pinning by GPC is enforced by (quasi)pinning of the collective Pauli constraint S2,9subscript𝑆29S_{2,9}, i.e. a universal estimate of the form D27(4,10)​(λ→)≤c27(4,10)​S2,9​(λ→)superscriptsubscript𝐷27410→𝜆superscriptsubscript𝑐27410subscript𝑆29→𝜆D_{27}^{(4,10)}(\vec{\lambda})\leq c_{27}^{(4,10)}\,S_{2,9}(\vec{\lambda}) follows with some geometric prefactor c27(4,10)superscriptsubscript𝑐27410c_{27}^{(4,10)} Tennie et al. (2017). Comparing the values for S2,9subscript𝑆29S_{2,9} and D27(4,10)superscriptsubscript𝐷27410D_{27}^{(4,10)} shows that the quasipinning by GPC D27(4,10)superscriptsubscript𝐷27410D_{27}^{(4,10)} for the Beryllium triplet state (without angular degrees of freedom) as discussed in the main text is non-trivial by a factor

Appendix C Calculation of the GPC for (N,d)=(3,11),(3,12)𝑁𝑑311312(N,d)=(3,11),(3,12)

In this section we describe on a rather elementary level the general strategy used for calculating the GPC for a fixed setting (N,d)𝑁𝑑(N,d). For further technical and mathematical details on this highly involved procedure we refer the reader to Ref. Altunbulak and Klyachko (2008); Altunbulak (2008).

As noted above, the GPC together with ordering constraints and normalization condition define a polytope 𝒫(N,d)superscript𝒫𝑁𝑑\mathcal{P}^{(N,d)}, called the ‘moment polytope’. In theory, for any setting (N,d)𝑁𝑑(N,d) the moment polytope is characterized by Theorem 2 and Theorem 9, respectively Altunbulak and Klyachko (2008). Both theorems suggest different algorithms for calculating the GPC defining the polytope 𝒫(N,d)superscript𝒫𝑁𝑑\mathcal{P}^{(N,d)} Altunbulak and Klyachko (2008); Altunbulak (2008). On the one hand, according the Theorem 2, the GPC are explicitly given by linear inequalities subject to a topological condition. This condition depends explicitly on so-called ‘test spectra’ and two permutations involved in the underlying mathematical problem (see Altunbulak and Klyachko (2008); Altunbulak (2008)). In practice, this means to check the topological condition for all test spectra and permutations which, however, becomes computationally very expensive for not too small settings (N,d)𝑁𝑑(N,d). Hence, the algorithm based on Theorem 2 allows one to calculate some of the GPC but typically not all of them, and thus leads to an outer approximation 𝒫o​u​t(N,d)superscriptsubscript𝒫𝑜𝑢𝑡𝑁𝑑\mathcal{P}_{out}^{(N,d)} to 𝒫(N,d)superscript𝒫𝑁𝑑\mathcal{P}^{(N,d)}. Theorem 9, on the other hand, describes the moment polytope as the convex hull of very specific spectra. Those spectra can be obtained from the irreducible components of the symmetric powers up to a finite degree M𝑀M of an irreducible U​(d)𝑈𝑑U(d)-representation, where U​(d)𝑈𝑑U(d) is the group of unitary operators of a d𝑑d-dimensional Hilbert space. The full polytope 𝒫(N,d)superscript𝒫𝑁𝑑\mathcal{P}^{(N,d)} can be obtained in that way only if M𝑀M is chosen large enough. Since in practice for larger settings (N,d)𝑁𝑑(N,d) not all of the required irreducible components can be calculated this procedure leads to a convex hull of spectra defining a subset 𝒫i​n(N,d)superscriptsubscript𝒫𝑖𝑛𝑁𝑑\mathcal{P}_{in}^{(N,d)} of the full polytope 𝒫(N,d)superscript𝒫𝑁𝑑\mathcal{P}^{(N,d)}.

Although the algorithms based on Theorem 2 and Theorem 9 are both typically too expensive for deriving all GPC, combining them allows one to calculate all GPC for much larger settings. The following procedure has proven to be the most efficient one:

  • (1)

    Calculate an inner polytope 𝒫i​n(N,d)superscriptsubscript𝒫𝑖𝑛𝑁𝑑\mathcal{P}_{in}^{(N,d)}.

  • (2)

    Identify all facets of the inner polytope found in step (1) which fit into the form of Theorem 2 in Altunbulak and Klyachko (2008). These facets define an outer polytope 𝒫o​u​t(N,d)superscriptsubscript𝒫𝑜𝑢𝑡𝑁𝑑\mathcal{P}_{out}^{(N,d)}.

  • (3)

    If both approximations coincide, 𝒫i​n(N,d)=𝒫o​u​t(N,d)superscriptsubscript𝒫𝑖𝑛𝑁𝑑superscriptsubscript𝒫𝑜𝑢𝑡𝑁𝑑\mathcal{P}_{in}^{(N,d)}=\mathcal{P}_{out}^{(N,d)}, one has obtained the full moment polytope 𝒫(N,d)=𝒫i​n(N,d)=𝒫o​u​t(N,d)superscript𝒫𝑁𝑑superscriptsubscript𝒫𝑖𝑛𝑁𝑑superscriptsubscript𝒫𝑜𝑢𝑡𝑁𝑑\mathcal{P}^{(N,d)}=\mathcal{P}_{in}^{(N,d)}=\mathcal{P}_{out}^{(N,d)}. Otherwise, one needs to continue the process by calculating larger inner polytopes 𝒫i​n(N,d)superscriptsubscript𝒫𝑖𝑛𝑁𝑑\mathcal{P}_{in}^{(N,d)}.

Further details can be found in Altunbulak and Klyachko (2008); Altunbulak (2008).

For small settings as, e.g., (N,d)=(3,6),(3,7)𝑁𝑑3637(N,d)=(3,6),(3,7) the algorithm works very well. For larger settings, however, one needs an additional tool to calculate the full set of GPC. The reason for this is that the inner polytope 𝒫i​n(N,d)superscriptsubscript𝒫𝑖𝑛𝑁𝑑\mathcal{P}_{in}^{(N,d)} may have ‘bad facets’, i.e. there are some spectral inequalities which do not fit into the form of Theorem 2 and thus it is not possible to verify the validity of a respective topological condition. Therefore, one needs to verify numerically whether such a spectral inequality represents a proper GPC: By minimizing a linear form of the one-particle reduced density matrix one can determine in a brute-force approach extremal points (vertices) of the polytope 𝒫(N,d)superscript𝒫𝑁𝑑\mathcal{P}^{(N,d)} (since any linear form attains its minimum at extremal points (vertices) of the convex polytope 𝒫(N,d)superscript𝒫𝑁𝑑\mathcal{P}^{(N,d)}). By comparing the vertices of the bad facet with those obtained by this numerical procedure, one can verify whether the respective spectral inequality represents a proper GPC or not.

A second computational problem concerns the verification of the topological condition mentioned above. The computational time for this verification depends exponentially on the length of the underlying permutations. While for the settings (3,d)3𝑑(3,d) with d≤11𝑑11d\leq 11 all required topological conditions could be verified on a personal computer, there have been 15 inequalities for the setting (3,12)312(3,12) where even high-performance computing hardware that is accessible to us at ETH could not provide the resources necessary for the verification. Instead, for those 15 inequalities we have successfully used the numerical procedure.

Finally, we also would like to stress that the software packages LiE Cohen et al. (2000) and Convex Franz (2016) were essential for the calculation for the GPC for the settings (3,11),(3,12)311312(3,11),(3,12).

Appendix D Variational method

If not indicated otherwise, all calculations for the Li and Be atoms have been carried out with the quantum-chemical program package DALTON DAL (2015); Aidas et al. (2014) using the parallel version of the full configuration interaction (CI) module LUCITA Knecht et al. (2008). Solving for the lowest state in a given spin and spatial symmetry, the variational FCI calculations were performed based on a Davidson subspace approach with a residual threshold of 10-7 hartree with respect to the energy. The natural occupation numbers were subsequently obtained as eigenvalues of the one-particle reduced density matrix that was calculated by means of the respective, converged FCI vector.

Appendix E Numerical data

We present in the following for each FCI calculation the largest 17 natural occupation numbers. For the Be atom restricted to the triplet spin sector with fixed magnetization M=+1𝑀1M=+1 we chose as atomic orbital (AO) basis sets 191919 (“Be triplet 1”), 212121 (“Be triplet 2”), 232323 (“Be triplet 3”), 242424 (“Be triplet 4”) and 252525 (“Be triplet 5”) s𝑠s-type functions (angular momentum functions with l=0𝑙0l=0) by starting from the triply-augmented aug-cc-pVQZ basis set Dunning Jr. (1989) and systematically adding diffuse s𝑠s-functions while simultaneously discarding all exponents for angular momentum functions with l>0𝑙0l>0. For the case of the lowest-lying quintet state of the Be atom we chose the aug-cc-CVQZ basis set Dunning Jr. (1989) in uncontracted form and augmented with angular momentum functions of up to i𝑖i-type (l=6𝑙6l=6), denoted as [22​s​18​p​14​d​8​f​5​g​4​h​1​i]delimited-[]22𝑠18𝑝14𝑑8𝑓5𝑔4ℎ1𝑖[22s18p14d8f5g4h1i], comprising in total 427 primitive AO functions. To determine the ground state of the Li atom we proceeded in two ways. First, the aug-cc-CVQZ atomic orbital basis set Dunning Jr. (1989) in uncontracted form was augmented by adding two diffuse functions for each l𝑙l quantum number up to l=4𝑙4l=4 (g𝑔g-functions) resulting in a total of 222 primitive AO functions (“Li doublet 1”, [18s12p8d6f4g]). In a second step, we augmented the original aug-cc-pCVQZ basis set by adding tight functions for each l𝑙l quantum number up l=4𝑙4l=4 and further included functions of hℎh- and i𝑖i-type leading to a total of 362 (“Li doublet 2”) and 517 (“Li doublet 3”) primitive AOs that can be best summarized as [20s17p11d8f5g2h1i] and [22s20p15d10f7g4h2i] AO basis sets, respectively. Finally, the variational FCI optimization of the lowest-lying quadruplet spin state of Li (“Li quadruplet”) was carried out by employing the “Li doublet 3” basis set.

Tables 2 and 3 compile the coefficients in the exponents of all atomic-orbital Gaussian basis sets employed in this work and described above. The basis set for the Be triplet calculation with five s functions (see Table 1 in the main text) is available upon request from the authors.

By comparing the results of the different Be triplet state calculations shown in Table 4 we conclude that the natural occupation numbers have converged on at least seven digits. For the Li doublet ground and quadruplet excited states summarized in Table 5 we observe convergence on the fourth, probably also on the fifth digit. Our best variational energy for the Be (Li) atom in the S1superscript𝑆1{}^{1}S (S2superscript𝑆2{}^{2}S) ground state obtained with the largest uncontracted AO basis set outlined above is -14.6667932644 hartree (-7.4778376184 hartree) which is well below millihartree accuracy compared to the present variational upper bounds for Be Puchalski et al.
